TEBPSK: pt. 9. This one is especially for my young professionals. A lot of us are conditioned to “just be grateful” we’re in certain spaces at all, and when it’s time to speak up or ask for things we don’t always feel empowered to use our voice. Know that there’s nothing wrong with asking for additional resources to help you perform better on the job. You’ll have to advocate for yourself a LOT on the job, and in general as you navigate life as a Black person in just about every setting. Exercise using your voice now. Happy Black History, Present & Future 🖤✨

A little baking soda and vinegar go a long way. Food and other dirt can get stuck in dishwasher filters so a deep clean every once in a while keeps everything sanitized. I learned this cleaning tip from one of my favorite accounts @carolina.mccauley, and I had so much fun trying it!

To say I’m honored to lead a conversation with @briannaholt in celebration of her book, In Our Shoes, is an understatement. I have so many feels, pride being one of the strongest. I met my Bri about 7 years ago at BuzzFeed and we instantly clicked. She soon started calling me “mom” because of my protective nature and my go-to “they jealous of you” response whenever anyone tried her. (I still stand by this!) 

Reading In Our Shoes started as preparation for this beautiful occasion, but it soon turned into such an empowering and insightful experience. Like every other Black women, Bri has LIVED. The intersection of Blackness and womanhood is indeed magic, but it’s also hard and often isolating. And she perfectly captures the beauty and the pain and the larger context through her own anecdotes. It’s a read that will make Black women feel seen and validated, and it’ll challenge everyone else to be allies with real action. But we’ll get into all that next week, 04/12, at @mcnallyjackson Seaport in nyc. RSVP in my stories & in @briannaholt’s bio! See you all there 💕

If you’re in Charlotte, NC, @leah_and_louise is a must! Inspired by Mississippi River Valley foodways, the black-owned restaurant does its own take on traditional southern dishes. Cocktails are also fab. Can’t wait to go back next time I’m in Charlotte!

Went to @themonkeykingnyc in Brooklyn and it was a perfect experience. Y’all know I love good food and an elevated, chic aesthetic so I was sold. The restaurant is also owned by children of Bengali and Chinese immigrants and I am obsessed with the way they’re carrying their culture and family legacy on through their own interpretation and experience as Asian Americans. @bushwickdaily did a really cool writeup on them, which I’ll link in my stories, if you wanna read more on the backstory. Anyway, check them out if you love dining out as much as I do ✨

My first time writing for @essence print, and it’s a story about me & my hair. The young girl in me is so overjoyed! Essence has unapologetically prioritized Black women’s stories since its inception, and to contribute to this culture-shifting publication in this way feels surreal 🥹🙏🏿❤️. 

Thank you @akili_ and everyone at @essence for having me — I’m so honored beyond what I could ever express. And thank you @ac.hampton, my @albanystateuniversity brother, for lending your lens and time to capture one of my favorite photos of me ever. God, you, the wind & my braid-out were all on the same page that day and I never could’ve imagined this photo would end up here! 

Go get the Jan/Feb ‘24 issue of @essence magazine w. @erikaalexanderthegreat, @issarae & @traceeellisross on the cover, y’all! And somebody at Essence email Susan Taylor and tell her I love her and her braids with my whole being 😭❤️. My girl @kaylaagreaves also has a story in here and it’s ca-uuuuuuute! Whew, the best way to close the year. See y’all in ‘24 (also unrelated but it’s Capricorn ♑️ 💜🐐 season).
